\begin_layout Paragraph

\emph on
Source Drop in Critical Reactor.
 
\emph default
Analyze the source drop into a critical reactor specified in the homework
 problem 4 of chapter 6 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ott1985"

\end_inset

.
 Specifically, determine the two reduced source magnitudes to yield the
 flux amplitude in Fig.
 6.22 by running the point kinetics program for various source magnitudes,
 and show the flux magnitude for the initial 900 seconds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because this problem involves a source drop, the explicit form of the point
 kinetics equations numerical method must be used.
 This form is given from the notes as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{n-1}=\left[\left(\rho_{n-1}-\beta\right)p_{n-1}+\sum_{k=1}^{6}\lambda_{k}\zeta_{k}^{(n-1)}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}=p_{n-1}+\frac{h}{\Lambda}R_{n-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\zeta_{k}^{(n)}=\left(1-\lambda_{k}h\right)\zeta_{k}^{(n-1)}+\beta_{k}hp_{n-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To include the independent source, we must modify these equations to include
 that source.
 The point kinetics equation including independent source neutrons is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{p}\left(t\right)=\frac{\rho-\beta}{\Lambda}p\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\Lambda}\sum_{k=1}^{6}\lambda_{k}\zeta_{k}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\Lambda}s\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

To modify the numerical method to include this, we simply add the source
 neutrons to the power equation, giving us
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{n-1}=\left[\left(\rho_{n-1}-\beta\right)p_{n-1}+\sum_{k=1}^{6}\lambda_{k}\zeta_{k}^{(n-1)}+s_{0}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To use the explicit form, we also need to be sure to use an appropriate
 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 value, because the explicit method is only stable for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h<\frac{1}{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

, we use the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{P}=\frac{\rho-\beta}{\Lambda}=\frac{-\beta}{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

, so the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 value should be half of that.
 Notice that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{P}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
negative
\series default
, so 
\series bold
it is likely that the explicit method never converges
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To derive the implicit method for a source drop problem, we start with the
 following equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{p_{n}-p_{n-1}}{h}=\frac{1}{\Lambda}\left[\left(\rho_{n}-\beta\right)p_{n}+\sum_{k=1}^{6}\lambda_{k}\zeta_{k}^{(n)}+s_{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and then using algebra, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Lambda}{h}p_{n-1}+s_{n}=\left[\frac{\Lambda}{h}+\left(\beta-\rho_{n}\right)\right]p_{n}-\sum_{k=1}^{6}\lambda_{k}\zeta_{k}^{(n)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To do that, we have the coefficient matrix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{A}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{1}{h}+\lambda_{1} &  &  & -\beta_{1}\\
 & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
 &  & \frac{1}{h}+\lambda_{6} & -\beta_{6}\\
-\lambda_{1} & \cdots & -\lambda_{6} & \frac{\Lambda}{h}+\left(\beta-\rho_{n}\right)
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the solution vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{b}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\zeta_{1}^{(n-1)}}{h}\\
\vdots\\
\frac{\zeta_{6}^{(n-1)}}{h}\\
\frac{\Lambda p_{n-1}}{h}+s_{n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, with those created, the solution of the problem 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\vec{x}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 can be found, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\zeta_{1}^{n}\\
\vdots\\
\zeta_{6}^{n}\\
p_{n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

