\begin_layout Paragraph

\emph on
Asymmetric Saw-tooth Reactivity Insertion
\emph default
.
 Analyze the reactivity transients specified in the homework problem 2 of
 Chapter 8, where an asymmetric saw-tooth reactivity insertion means the
 reactivity transient in Eq.
 (1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\left(t\right)=\begin{cases}
at, & t\leq t_{1}\\
at_{1}-a^{'}\left(t-t_{1}\right), & t>t_{1}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Use 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}=0.1\, s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=5\,\$/s$
\end_inset

, and five different ramp rate values on the declining part; 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{'}=a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{'}=0.75a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{'}=0.5a$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{'}=0.25a$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{'}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Plot the power amplitude and its derivative for initial 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3\, s$
\end_inset

 and estimate the time for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{p}=0$
\end_inset

 and the reactivity at this time point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a reactivity transient, the implicit numerical method derived in the
 notes can be applied and solved for each step.
 This method is unconditionally stable, so the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is trivial, but should still give enough resolution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method is simple to program.
 In general, for each time step, the coefficient matrix is created in arrowhead
 form, as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{A}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\frac{1}{h}+\lambda_{1} &  &  & -\beta_{1}\\
 & \ddots &  & \vdots\\
 &  & \frac{1}{h}+\lambda_{6} & -\beta_{6}\\
-\lambda_{1} & \cdots & -\lambda_{6} & \frac{\Lambda}{h}+\left(\beta-\rho_{n}\right)
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
and then the vector can be filled with the previous step solutions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{b}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{\zeta_{1}^{(n-1)}}{h}\\
\vdots\\
\frac{\zeta_{6}^{(n-1)}}{h}\\
\frac{\Lambda p_{n-1}}{h}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, with those created, the solution of the problem 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\vec{x}=\vec{b}$
\end_inset

 can be found, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{x}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\zeta_{1}^{n}\\
\vdots\\
\zeta_{6}^{n}\\
p_{n}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solving can be done by gaussian elimination and backsubstitution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bradie2006"

\end_inset

, but in this case the MATLAB backdivision operator 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mathworks2013"

\end_inset

 was used to save time in programming.
\end_layout

